featured_reviews.review_id: Fakhr Ul Masajid or Pride of Mosques or Lal Masjid and also known as Sikandar Sahib's Masjid is situated in Bara Bazaar, Kashmiri Gate area in Old Delhi. It was built by Kaniz I Fatima who was entitled as Fakhr i Jahan in 1728-29 AD in the memory of her beloved husband Shujaat Khan who was a noble in the Court of Aurangzeb. This mosque has seen many damages but were repaired. It's an excellent example of Indo Islamic architecture.

featured_reviews.review_id:
Introduction-

Jamia Masjid Sopore is one of the historical religious place in Sopore town. Located on the banks of mesmerising Jhelum, the place puts you in awe.

Details-

I personally like the Masjid's first floor. It is abide of heaven during summer. It can be chilling in winter, hence congregation shifts to ground floor during winter.
I like the park in front. Always well maintained and full of Creativity. The gardener might be an creative artist.

Overall review-

Keep up the quality.
Let us keep praying for peace in the valley.

featured_reviews.review_id:
This is the Heart of Sopore Town. A Lovely Masjid Located Right On The Bank Of River Jhelum. A Very Vibrant Place With A Lot Of Historical Background!

The Masjid is a very grand one and houses two floors with the first floor being used during the summers and the ground floor during winters.

Besides that the Masjid has a well maintained Lawn that presents a beautiful view of the flowing River Jhelum.

featured_reviews.review_id:
A beautiful masjid located along the banks of the river Jehlum. Is situated alongside the Hatisha Bridge.
It's also called as Jamia Qadim.
The Jamia Qadim is located on the right bank of River Jhelum within its own ground which is well-vegetated and rests on a high embankment. The lawn is well maintained. The masjid seemed well maintained too although I didn't go inside.

featured_reviews.review_id: The Jamia Qadim masjid of Sopore is a T-shaped building with the longer, linear side having north-size axis. And measuring around 54m x 22m. The main entrance on the eastern via a modern porch. Internally the building comprises a single hall divided into three longitudinal bays parallel to the kibla west .. The central bay comprises a double height space, with clearstory lighting. Three high spires brangh rise from the three ridge ends of the roof which is hipped type. The materials used in the construction of this building include burnt bricks, cement mortar, wooden door window, frames and panels. The outer face of the building is done in burnt bricks in cement pointing. The building has a central, continuous dub, running the length of the second floor. Internally the building is cement plastered in the ground floor, while as the first and the second floor walls are plastered in mud. The ceiling of the building comprises wooden beams running through and through.
